    <h1>Linux Commands Reference</h1>

    <h2>ðŸ’» System Information</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><code>uname</code> - Print system information</li>
        <li><code>uname -a</code> - All system information</li>
        <li><code>uname -r</code> - Kernel release</li>
        <li><code>uname -m</code> - Machine hardware name</li>
        <li><code>uptime</code> - Show how long system has been running</li>
        <li><code>date</code> - Display or set the system date/time</li>
        <li><code>who</code> - Show who is logged on</li>
        <li><code>whoami</code> - Print effective userid</li>
        <li><code>id</code> - Print user and group IDs</li>
        <li><code>which</code> - Locate a command in PATH</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>ðŸ‘‘ Privilege & Administration</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><code>sudo</code> - Execute command as superuser</li>
        <li><code>su</code> - Switch user (or become superuser)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>âš¡ System Control</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><code>shutdown</code> - Shutdown or restart system</li>
        <li><code>reboot</code> - Reboot the system</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>ðŸ“¦ Package Management (Debian/Ubuntu)</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><code>apt</code> - Advanced Package Tool (modern)</li>
        <li><code>apt-get</code> - APT package handling utility (legacy)</li>
    </ul>

